#=================================#
# The different ZFS Vdevs layouts #
#=================================#==================================================================================================#

   • STRIPE:
      2 or more drives. All storage space and highest performance, no fault tolerance

   • MIRROR:
      Needs 2 drive. Half storage space and high read speed but standard write speed, fault tolerance 1 drive

   • STRIPE + MIRROR:
      Striped mirror pool is a large, fast, reliable but expensive storage space. Half storage space, can lose a disk on each mirror.

   • RAIDZ:
      Raidz fits as large, reliable, relatively cheap storage.
      Raidz sometimes called RAIDZ1, is most similar to a traditional RAID5 and requires minimum of 3 disks to be meaningful.
      Like in a regular RAID5, every "row" along with the data blocks stores a parity function calculated over the data blocks
      which allows a system to survive a single disk failure.

   • RAIDZ2: 
      RAIDZ2 is a large, highly reliable, relatively expensive storage, which requires a minimum of 4 disks to be meaningful.
      RAIDZ2 is like RAID6 – allows to survive a double disk failure at the expense of storing two different parity functions.
      All considerations about block placement pattern and block size are the same as for a RAIDZ. 

   • RAIDZ3
      Needs 5 Drives to be meaningful. Triple parity RAID.
      Although back in 2009 people discussed that triple-parity RAID should replace the traditional RAID5/6 and ensure data integrity even during massive hardware failures or during long resilvering processes. Had even proposed a name – RAID7
      only in the ZFS environment the triple-parity RAID idea has been developed and implemented in full.
      With RAIDZ3, you can create a storage system, which allows to tolerate 3 disk failures before losing data. 

   • dRAID
      Distributed RAID. A vdev that provides distributed parity and hot spares across multiple drives
      allowing for much faster rebuild performance after a failure. (For large arrays only)


