#====================================================#
# ZFS offers alternative usage for drives like SSD's #
#====================================================#===============================================================================#

                    *** Don't partition your fast NVMe, use Zvols to accelerate your HDD storage ***

   • SPECIAL VDEV  (The Game Changer for HDD!)
      A drive that store only metadata and optional small files

   • USAGE: Game changer on HDD zpools, use only in very specific cases on NVME

   • EXAMPLE FOR SSD: If you have two 1 TB gen3 NVME and one smaller 500GB gen4 NVME
      use the gen3 in stripe and add the gen4 as special vdev for metadata and small files < 64k/128k/256k. 
      Or one gen5 and two gen4 NVME
      The same principle can be used if you have one NVME
      and a larger zpool of SATA SSD use the NVME as special vdev for the SATA SSD zpool.


   • If you have a zpool consisting of one or more HDD - USE SPECIAL VDEV 


                             !! Always mirror your Special VDEV if your data is important!!
      !! The special vdev gets married to your zpool, if you remove it or your special vdev drive dies, your zpool dies !!


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

   • SLOG (Log)
      All ZFS pools have a built-in log called the ZIL (ZFS Intent Log),
      which is stored on the pool's regular hard drives for security reasons.
      An SLOG is simply a separate and much faster disk that you assign to this task
      When to use it: It is used only for synchronous writes. This is common in environments with databases,
      virtualization (such as Qemu/Virt-manager or Proxmox),
      and nil sharing via NFS and iSCSI. Performance boost: Since ZFS guarantees that data is safely in the log immediately,
      the system does not have to wait for the hard drives to write data to its final destination. This significantly reduces latency

   • USAGE: In a home PC, there is not much need for a slog if you run your system on NVME.
      If you have a zpool consisting of one or more HDD you can use it to minimize latency and increase performance.
      HHD storage/system zpool - Use Slog 


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

   • L2ARC (Cache)
      Level 2 Adaptive Replacement Cache, is an OpenZFS feature that extends the main memory (ARC)
      cache onto faster storage media, like SSDs or NVMe drives.
      It is designed to accelerate read performance for large,
      random read workloads by holding frequently accessed data that overflows from your system's RAM.
      RAM Overhead: Every block stored in the L2ARC requires an in-memory header in the primary ARC
      (approximately 96 to 116 bytes per block, depending on the ZFS version) so ZFS knows where to find it.
      If your PC is low on RAM, adding an enormous L2ARC can starve your primary cache

   • USAGE: Do not use L2arc in a home PC except for HHD zpools. 
      If you have a zpool consisting of one or more HDD use L2ARC!


                       *** Don't partition your fast NVMe, use Zvols to accelerate your HDD storage ***  


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

   • Spare
     A drive that acts as a hot spare, automatically replacing a failed drive in another vdev.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

   • Dedup
      A vdev dedicated strictly to storing the Deduplication Table (DDT).


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

   • ZVOL
      A virtual block device, it is a "real device" for the system, you can use this for many things.
      let's assume your system is running on one or more SSD/NVME and you want to create a larger HHD zpool for storage
      you can create ZVOL's on your SSD/NVME zpool and then create Slog, special vedev or L2ARC of these ZVOL's
      to increase the performance of your HHD storage zpool.

      It is also the absolute best to use for virtual machines,
      creating a zvol to install a VM on gives you the best you can get for a VM.
 
   • EXAMPLE:
      you can create a ZVOL and install Windows on it, now you have checksum, ARC cache, snapshots on your windows VM.
      Your Windows VM now runs faster than a standard Windows with NTFS alone - ZFS is the king


                         !! Remember that if you make a Special vdev it cant be removed afterwards !!


